Data Description

The data for this project come from end of semester student evaluations for a large sample of professors from The University of Texas at Austin. The original data set published in Beauty in the Classroom (Hamermesh & Parker, 2005) are available through the openintro R package.

For the Midterm Project, my analysis focused on the relationship between professorâs attractiveness and course evaluation scores, two numerical variables. For this analysis, however, I will be focusing on two categorical variables:

  • professorâs self-identified sex (M / F)
  • professorâs teaching rank (teaching / tenure track / tenured)

Specifically, I am interested in investigating if there are larger proportions of male-identifying faculty in tenured positions, whereas there are larger proportions of women in teaching positions.

Independence of Professorâs Sex and Teaching Rank

For our chi-squared analysis, we are interested in knowing if a professorâs sex is independent of their teaching rank. If there was no relationship between sex and teaching rank, we would expect to see approximately equal proportions of male identifying faculty across the teaching ranks.

Model Conditions

To conduct a chi-squared analysis, there are two conditions required to be checked, (1) independence of observations and (2) expected cell counts of at least five for every level of sex and teaching rank.

As these professors were a convenience sample of professors at UT Austin, not a random sample, we need to think carefully about independence. There are no repeated observations of professors in the dataset and knowing the sex and rank of one faculty member doesnât give you perfect information about another faculty member. Thus, I do not believe the independence of observations condition is violated.

The table of observed counts is shown below. The smallest observed counts are for female and male teaching faculty. To perform a parametric chi-squared analysis, we are required to have five expected counts in each cell of the table. Based on the table, we can see that the cell which should have the lowest expected count is female, teaching faculty. The expected count for this cell is \(\frac{40 \times 15}{94} = 6.382\), which is larger than 5.

rank female male Total
teaching 8 7 15
tenure track 14 11 25
tenured 18 36 54
Total 40 54 94

Since I have not seen any major violations of these conditions, I believe using a parametric chi-squared distribution will not incorrectly estimate the p-value for the test of independence.

Chi-Squared Analysis

The results of the chi-squared analysis are presented below.

statistic chisq_df p_value
4.440049 2 0.1086064

With a p-value of 0.109 (chi-squared statistic = 4.4 on 2 degrees of freedom), we have weak evidence against the null. At an \(\alpha\) of 0.1 we fail to reject the null hypothesis of independence. Hence, these data do not suggest that a professorâs sex and their teaching rank are dependent.
